kg.Battle of Jupiter Inlet: {"Battle of Jupiter Inlet": {"date": "January 15, 1838","participants": ["Seminole Indians","Seminole Negro","United States Navy"],"location": "Jupiter Inlet, Florida","description": "The Battle of Jupiter Inlet, also known as the First Battle of Loxahatchee, was fought between the Seminole Indians - Seminole Negro and the United States Navy. The Navy spotted a trail alongside the Jupiter Inlet, and seventy-five men were landed to find the Seminole camp nearby. The camp was led by Sam Jones, Ar-pi-uck-i, the spiritual medicine and war chief of the Miccosukee and Seminole people during the war. The officers that advanced on the camp were outnumbered and ambushed. After a long fight, the US retreated with five men killed in action and about twenty others wounded. Lt. kg.Ira Deutchman: {"story": "Ira Deutchman is a prominent figure in the independent film industry, known for his work as a producer, distributor, and marketer of independent films. In 2000, he co-founded and managed Emerging Pictures, a digital exhibition company in New York, until its sale in 2015. Deutchman has also made significant contributions to academia, serving as the Chair of the Film Program at Columbia University School of the Arts and as a Professor of Professional Practice for over 25 years. His involvement in industry organizations and institutions like The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, the Sundance Institute, and various film festivals has further solidified his impact on the independent film community. Deutchman continues to produce films, consult on marketing and distribution, and teach producing students at Columbia University's School of the Arts.","title": "Ira Deutchman's Impact on Independent Film","year": "2021"}
kg.Mariana Castillo Deball: {"story": "Mariana Castillo Deball is an artist born in Mexico City in 1975. She studied at the Universidad Nacional Autónoma de México, Mexico City and the Jan Van Eyck Academie in Maastricht. Currently, she is based in Berlin. In 2009, she was awarded the Ars Viva prize. Castillo Deball explores the role objects play in our understanding of identity and history using installation, sculpture, photography, and drawing. She engages in prolonged periods of research and field work, taking on the role of the explorer or the archaeologist. In 2013, she created the work Stelae Storage, featuring plaster casts copied from monolithic Mayan stone sculptures displayed on metal racks. She also produced Lost Magic Kingdoms Paolozzi in the same year, using photographic reproductions from the personal archives of the late Scottish artist Eduardo Paolozzi, who mixed pop and ethnographic references.","title": "Mariana Castillo Deball's Artistic Career","year": 2013}

kg.M\u00e9diath\u00e8que Musicale Mahler: {"story": "The Médiathèque Musicale Mahler is a multimedia library with collections relating to music of the 19th and 20th centuries. It was founded in 1986 as the Bibliothèque Gustav Mahler by Henry-Louis de La Grange and Maurice Fleuret. The library's holdings include original manuscript scores, letters, and other documents, and published scores, books, periodicals, press clippings, recordings, and other personal archives. The current president of the library is Pierre Bergé.","title": "Médiathèque Musicale Mahler","year": 1986}

kg.Sv\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1: {"dumplingsPreparation": {"name": "Houskové knedlíky","description": "Houskové knedlíky, also known as bread dumplings, are a traditional Czech side dish commonly served with svíčková. kg.Cola chicken: {"dumplingsPreparation": {"name": "Cola Chicken","mainIngredients": ["chicken", "cola soft drink"],"optionalIngredients": ["soy sauce", "barbecue sauce", "ketchup"],"variations": ["regular cola", "diet cola"],"description": "Cola chicken is a chicken dish prepared using chicken and cola soft drink as main ingredients. It can have a sticky texture, depending on how it is prepared. Cola chicken has been described as a dish that has flavor elements of sweet and sour, and the cola has been described as imparting a rich flavor in the chicken meat."}}
